sub_title: PhD AI Researcher at The Netherlands Cancer Institute
summary: I have recently completed my MSc studies in Artificial Intelligence at Imperial College London and my aim is to obtain a mixture of further theoretical and applied knowledge by specializing in applicable areas, such as Health Care or Computer Vision, through further studies and research (PhD). My objective is to contribute to the field and unlock hidden and undiscovered areas while aiming to improve our quality of life. I am a hardworking individual, with a proven track record of academic excellence (MSc GPA: 82.6, BSc GPA: 9.46/10, High School grade 19.75/20). In summer 2019, I graduated from the University of Cyprus with a BSc in Mathematics and I was the student with the highest GPA within the Faculty of Pure and Applied Sciences. Additionally, as a senior student, I was very honoured to receive the “Cyprus Mathematical Award” granted to the senior student of the Department of Mathematics and Statistics with the best academic performance. In 2018, I was selected to participate in the Erasmus student exchange program. I always enjoy teamwork and I have many participations in extra-curriculum events and competitions, while on several occasions I have earned awards. During my free time, I like being involved in voluntary work and relevant campaigns and I also enjoy playing tennis, cooking, and travelling.

projects:
[{'title': 'Computational approach for the Orr-Sommerfeld equation with the Finite Element Method', 'date': {'start': {'month': 8, 'day': None, 'year': 2018}, 'end': {'month': 6, 'day': None, 'year': 2019}}, 'description': "The goals of the current study are :
(1) to make an introduction into the Theory of Hydrodynamic Stability which studies
mechanisms that make a flow unstable,
(2) to present analytically the derivation of the Orr-Sommerfeld equation from the
Navier-Stokes equations which is a famous equation that occurs in Hydrodynamic Sta-
bility Theory,
(3) to present the Finite Element Method for calculating the eigenvalues of the Orr-Sommerfeld equation.
The Orr-Sommerfeld equation is an eigenvalue problem and it is a fourth-order, ordinary differential equation for the time variation of an in\x0cfitesimal disturbance velocity in a two-dimensional incompressible laminar flow. It is a central element of Hydrodynamic Stability theory. We further study the distribution of the derived eigenvalues for different choices of the parameters of the equation and observe numerically the method's convergence.", 'contributors': [{'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': 'George', 'last_name': 'Yiasemis', 'name': None, 'headline': 'PhD AI Researcher at The Netherlands Cancer Institute'}]}]
